# Commit message format

Every commit MUST use:

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

<body>
```

## Subject line

- Format: `<type>(<scope>): <subject>`
- Imperative mood ("add", not "added")
- Lowercase subject (after the colon)
- No trailing period
- Max ~72 characters for the subject line

## Body

- Required for non-trivial changes (always include for feat, fix, refactor)
- Blank line between subject and body
- Explain **why**, not a file list
- Wrap at ~72 characters

## Types

| Type       | Use for                              |
| ---------- | ------------------------------------ |
| `feat`     | New feature or user-visible behavior |
| `fix`      | Bug fix                              |
| `docs`     | Documentation only                   |
| `style`    | Formatting, no logic change          |
| `refactor` | Code change, no feature/fix          |
| `test`     | Tests only                           |
| `chore`    | Tooling, deps, config                |

## Scopes

| Scope    | Use for                                  |
| -------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `client` | React app (`client/`)                    |
| `server` | Express API (`server/`)                  |
| `docs`   | AGENTS.md, README, docs/, COMPONENTS.md  |
| `repo`   | Root config, cursor rules, cross-cutting |

Omit scope only for truly repo-wide changes: `chore: ...`

## Examples

```
docs(docs): add frontend plan and component reference

Document implementation phases and component tree so agents and
contributors can continue work without re-deriving architecture.
```

```
feat(client): add bundle reducer with variant quantity keys

Selections keyed by productId:variantId so card and review steppers
stay in sync per the take-home spec.
```

```
fix(client): show all variants with qty in review panel

Review lines now derive from every selection with qty > 0, not only
the active chip on the product card.
```

## When committing (agent)

1. Follow the existing git safety workflow (status, diff, log).
2. Draft subject + body in this format before `git commit`.
3. Pass the message via HEREDOC.
